{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_014SjhA377UDWVoJu7bDBgQu","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.example.realworldapi.application.web.model.response;\n     2→\n     3→import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonRootName;\n     4→import lombok.Getter;\n     5→import lombok.Setter;\n     6→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.model.user.User;\n     7→\n     8→@Getter\n     9→@Setter\n    10→@JsonRootName(\"profile\")\n    11→public class ProfileResponse {\n    12→\n    13→    private String username;\n    14→    private String bio;\n    15→    private String image;\n    16→    private boolean following;\n    17→\n    18→    public ProfileResponse(User user) {\n    19→        this.username = user.getUsername();\n    20→        this.bio = user.getBio();\n    21→        this.image = user.getImage();\n    22→    }\n    23→}\n    24→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1968c9d1-9222-41bb-9d6c-3e0081e3cb16","uuid":"509e6d2b-a6d8-4e59-9093-06bdd1ff7641"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01Kte65bMuwAYHC1SzJgiMtT","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.example.realworldapi.application.web.model.response;\n     2→\n     3→import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonFormat;\n     4→import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonRootName;\n     5→import lombok.Getter;\n     6→import lombok.NoArgsConstructor;\n     7→import lombok.Setter;\n     8→import org.example.realworldapi.domain.model.comment.Comment;\n     9→\n    10→import java.time.LocalDateTime;\n    11→import java.util.UUID;\n    12→\n    13→@Getter\n    14→@Setter\n    15→@NoArgsConstructor\n    16→@JsonRootName(\"comment\")\n    17→public class CommentResponse {\n    18→\n    19→    private UUID id;\n    20→\n    21→    @JsonFormat(shape = JsonFormat.Shape.STRING, pattern = \"yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH:mm:ss.SSS'Z'\")\n    22→    private LocalDateTime createdAt;\n    23→\n    24→    @JsonFormat(shape = JsonFormat.Shape.STRING, pattern = \"yyyy-MM-dd'T'HH:mm:ss.SSS'Z'\")\n    25→    private LocalDateTime updatedAt;\n    26→\n    27→    private String body;\n    28→    private ProfileResponse author;\n    29→\n    30→    public CommentResponse(Comment comment, ProfileResponse author) {\n    31→        this.id = comment.getId();\n    32→        this.createdAt = comment.getCreatedAt();\n    33→        this.updatedAt = comment.getUpdatedAt();\n    34→        this.body = comment.getBody();\n    35→        this.author = author;\n    36→    }\n    37→}\n    38→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1968c9d1-9222-41bb-9d6c-3e0081e3cb16","uuid":"cb770870-3424-4b21-8f3b-1e7ecaadd385"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01Fa75D5kzFg1HpwDFrVvYRH","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Good. I notice an important issue with the response wrapping. The `ArticleResponse` has `@JsonRootName(\"article\")` and `ProfileResponse` has `@JsonRootName(\"profile\")`. When the `wrapRootValueObjectMapper` serializes `ArticleResponse`, the nested `ProfileResponse author` field would also be wrapped since ALL objects with `@JsonRootName` would get wrapped in a wrapping ObjectMapper. This is problematic because the `author` field inside article should just be a nested object, not wrapped.\n\nActually, looking more closely: `WRAP_ROOT_VALUE` only wraps the **root** object being serialized. Nested objects within the root aren't affected by this setting. So `ArticleResponse` -> `{\"article\": {..., \"author\": {...}}}` is correct. The `author` ProfileResponse nested inside won't be double-wrapped.\n\nBut wait - there's another issue. When `ProfilesResource` serializes `ProfileResponse` with the wrapping ObjectMapper, it will produce `{\"profile\": {...}}` which is correct. And when `ArticlesResource` serializes the `ArticleResponse` for single articles, it will produce `{\"article\": {...}}` which is correct.\n\nFor the `noWrapObjectMapper` used in list responses (articlesResponse, commentsResponse), `ArticlesResponse` and `CommentsResponse` don't have `@JsonRootName`, so they'll just serialize their fields directly, producing `{\"articles\": [...], \"articlesCount\": N}` and `{\"comments\": [...]}` which is correct.\n\nNow let me create the smoke tests. Let me look at the request wrapper models to understand the exact JSON format."}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3157,"cache_read_input_tokens":61978,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":3157,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":642},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1968c9d1-9222-41bb-9d6c-3e0081e3cb16","uuid":"bac9100e-b389-4d73-89d6-751d07c54a51"}
